<font color="#FF0000">MY FIRST SILENT CHRISTMAS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 14 10:45:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To The Grunt, I shared your pain.<br><br>
Homecoming was very lonely for me, no one looked my way on my bus ride home, and when they did it was with the same indifference I had seen in the eyes of the Vietnamese civilians when I had first arrived in their country.<br><br>
I began to wonder then, what had happened to the America I had left behind.<br>
Had my country changed or had I?<br>
Was I so different, to merit stares when they did look?<br><br>
I didn’t know what had happened at home, didn’t know of the impact the protest, riots and anti-war movement had had on the country that had send me to war, but I knew that it wasn't the same country I had left behind.<br><br>
My First Christmas back, was also very lonely, still in the service but on leave Christmas 1968 with a wife that didn't understand nor want to know what had happened in Nam, the Silent Nights of that Christmas at home was very lonely.<br><br>
Sparrowhawk
